Allowed `event_stage` values:
{= event_stage_descriptions =}

Facet-to-stage fit:
{= facet_event_stage_requirements =}

For `initiation_tender_or_procurement`, cite the official record whose operative action opens or approves the procurement: a tender notice, declaration, procurement approval, ESIDIS/ADAM procurement notice, or tender document. A funding/program inclusion decision, preliminary program invitation, vendor page, operating page, or later status/regulation page does not satisfy initiation merely because it says the municipality joined a micromobility program or mentions a future procurement.

For `execution_award_or_contract`, cite the official award or contract-execution record: temporary or final award, contractor-selection decision, signed contract, KIMDIS/ADAM contract record, contract protocol, or official contract publication/registration. A tender-only source does not satisfy this facet. A YMEPERAA or other funding/program inclusion page does not satisfy this facet merely because it has a municipality-specific line, amount, MIS code, or subproject title. A later operating regulation or status page also does not satisfy this facet merely because it recites an old ADAM/protocol number; it counts for execution only if the URL actually exposes the separate operative award/contract record or attachment and the record identifies that award/contract action.

For `downstream_change_operation_or_status`, cite a post-procurement or post-award/contract official action or status for the same case: amendment, delivery/receipt/acceptance, extension, penalty/sanction, operating regulation, live official status or use-rule page, official launch/status notice, or a bounded official conflict/caveat tied to the procurement or contract. Pre-procurement funding/program inclusion is not downstream even when it is official and municipality-specific. The downstream record should carry enough source-backed anchor detail to make the relationship verifiable from that record when possible: a prior contract, award, tender, ADAM/KIMDIS/ESIDIS/protocol identifier or date; the downstream decision/action/status/date; or a clearly linked municipal system context.

Funding/program inclusion may be useful context in a record's ledger details, and sources from program authorities can be valid official sources when they expose an operative required facet. But a source that only includes or funds a municipality, allocates a budget, names a MIS/OPS code, or lists program beneficiaries is optional context, not one of the three counted lifecycle facets.

The three facet records should normally cite distinct official documents/URLs. Reusing one URL for multiple facets counts only when that URL genuinely exposes separate operative records or actions for the claimed facets, and the record's details and excerpts make clear which action supports each facet. Do not reuse one multipurpose document to claim a facet that appears only as background history.

Each record must name the official document or page and provide a concise official ledger summary for the claimed facet and stage: at least one visible stage-bearing date or official identifier when visible, plus vendor/consortium, amount, lifecycle status, or caveat only when that detail is central to the claimed stage or is reported for the record. Do not use vague placeholders such as "tender page", "decision", or only a year when the source shows a specific title, decision number, date, ADA/ADAM/KIMDIS/ESIDIS/protocol number, vendor, amount, or status. You do not need to transcribe every visible cross-reference from a multipurpose official document when the source, case, facet, stage, and reported details remain specific and source-bounded.

Requirements:
- The page must communicate that it is an official public source for the record: a fetchable official municipal page/PDF/minutes/committee decision, public-authority mirror that embeds Diavgeia/KIMDIS/ADAM/ESIDIS framing, KIMDIS/ADAM or ESIDIS public record that the browser can inspect, official public-authority decision, or official operating regulation/status page. Direct `https://diavgeia.gov.gr/doc/...` citation URLs do not count unless the cited page/PDF content is actually inspectable; use ADA identifiers as ledger details, not as a substitute for a fetchable source URL. Vendor websites, app-store pages, press/news pages, generic aggregators, search results, lead-generation mirrors, and promotional product pages do not count as primary evidence.
- The page must tie the procurement case to a Greek municipality and to a public bicycle-sharing, e-bike sharing, or municipal micromobility system procurement, contract, operating rule, or status.
- The page must match the submitted `lifecycle_facet`: initiation records must expose the operative tender/procurement-opening action, execution records must expose the operative award or contract action, and downstream records must expose a post-procurement or post-award/contract change, operation, status, or bounded official caveat. Background references inside funding, regulation, operating/status, later minutes, or implementation records do not satisfy a different facet unless the cited URL exposes a separate attached or embedded operative record for that different facet and the record points to it.
- The page must support the claimed `event_stage` with source-backed event details. Use the stage the cited page itself acts on or officially publishes: do not label tender notices as awards or contracts, program/funding pages as execution or downstream actions, operating/status pages as awards, later regulation/status pages as contracts, or contract-signing announcements as awards unless the same URL also plainly exposes the separate stage-bearing decision/record text. Skip a stage if the source only mentions it in passing or only lists it as background history.
- For `downstream_change_operation_or_status`, the page must show either a post-procurement/post-award action or official current/operating status and enough anchor detail to connect it to the municipal bike-share procurement or contract: prior procurement/award/contract identifier or date when visible, downstream action/status/date, or a clearly linked municipal system context. A program inclusion/funding decision is not downstream by itself.
- Reported dates, identifiers, vendors/consortia, amounts, statuses, and caveats must be visibly bounded by the official source. Vendor or consortium names count only when the official source states them. If a source does not visibly state vendor, amount, or final status, omit that detail or say it is not visible rather than importing it from another page.
